hyca51 wrote:

&gt; My test class:
&gt; public class StackTests {
&gt;       private Stack stack;
&gt;      
&gt;       @BeforeClass public void init() {
&gt;             stack = new SimpleStack();
&gt;       }
&gt;      
&gt;       @Test public void isEmpty() {
&gt;             Assert.assertTrue(stack.isEmpty());
&gt;       }
&gt;      
&gt;       static public junit.framework.Test suite() {
&gt;             return new JUnit4TestAdapter(StackTests.class);
&gt;       }
&gt; }

My guess is that @BeforeClass can only set class-level variables. This 
makes some sense, because @BeforeClass implies that there isn&#39;t 
necessarily an instance of the test case yet. It&#39;s not immediately 
obvious, but it makes sense after a few moments&#39; thought. If I were a 
beginner with Java and JUnit, it would confuse the hell out of me.

I think you should just use @Before and not @BeforeClass. Don&#39;t do 
class-level setup as a performance hack; it creates more problems than 
it solves.

